## PART X — ANTI-MISATTRIBUTION ENFORCEMENT

### Section 28. Fork Misattribution Defined

**28.1** Fork Misattribution occurs when a party:

> **(a)** Forks, copies, clones, or substantially reproduces a Formed Work
> covered by this License; AND

> **(b)** Represents, asserts, implies, or allows others to believe that
> the mathematical content of the fork — including theorems, proofs,
> algorithms, derivations, or formal verification structures — was
> independently derived by the forking party or by any party other than
> the Originating Maker identified in the applicable Prior Art Entry.

**28.2** Fork Misattribution includes but is not limited to:

- (a) Filing a patent application on mathematics appearing in a Prior Art Entry, citing no prior art
- (b) Publishing an academic paper claiming original derivation of mathematics appearing in a Prior Art Entry without citing the Prior Art Entry
- (c) Representing to investors, customers, or the public that a fork contains original mathematical innovations that are in fact covered by Prior Art Entries
- (d) Naming or renaming a fork in a manner designed to obscure its origin from the Formed Work
- (e) Removing, altering, or obscuring attribution headers, WORM seals, or Certification Marks from a fork

**28.3** Fork Misattribution is distinct from legitimate forking. A party may
fork this Work, modify it, extend it, and distribute it under this License
without restriction, provided they preserve attribution and do not misattribute
the Originating Maker's mathematical derivations.

### Section 29. Consequences of Fork Misattribution

**29.1** A party found by the Technical Review Panel to have committed Fork
Misattribution:

> **(a)** Immediately forfeits all rights under Parts III, IV, and VII
> of this License, including all Certification Mark privileges

> **(b)** Must remove all Certification Marks and all representations of
> certification, verification, or Registry standing within thirty (30) days

> **(c)** Must publish a public correction identifying the Originating Maker
> and the applicable Prior Art Entry in any venue where the misattribution
> appeared

> **(d)** Is referred to the Operator's legal counsel for evaluation of
> applicable fraud, misrepresentation, and IP theft remedies under the
> laws of the applicable jurisdiction

> **(e)** Is permanently barred from filing further Declarations of Formation
> or Certification applications unless the Technical Review Panel determines
> that the misattribution was inadvertent and the correction has been
> published

**29.2** The consequences in Section 29.1 do not affect the forking party's
right to use the Sovereign Substrate under Part II. Part II is irrevocable
and unconditional. What terminates is the registry standing, the mark rights,
and the representation of certification — not the underlying use right.

**29.3** The Operator may publish a public notice in the Sovereign Registry
identifying a party who has committed Fork Misattribution. This notice is
factual and is not subject to defamation claims to the extent it accurately
states the Technical Review Panel's determination.

### Section 30. Reporting Fork Misattribution

**30.1** Any person who believes Fork Misattribution has occurred may file
a complaint with the Operator at:

```
registry.snapkittywest.github.io/misattribution-complaint
```

**30.2** A complaint must include:

| Field | Required |
|-------|----------|
| Complainant identity | Yes |
| Respondent identity | Yes |
| The Prior Art Entry allegedly misattributed | Yes |
| The specific representation constituting the misattribution | Yes |
| Evidence (URLs, publications, screenshots) | Yes |
| Declaration that the complaint is made in good faith | Yes |

**30.3** The Operator will notify the respondent and provide thirty (30) days
to respond before convening the Technical Review Panel.

**30.4** Frivolous complaints made in bad faith may result in the complainant
being barred from future filings.

